ijk"},"en":{"1378–1450":"1378–1450","1373–1410":"1373–1410","1390–1420":"1390–1420","1378":"1378","1410":"1410","1420":"1420","1450":"1450","1373":"1373","1390":"1390","Ashbourne, Derbyshire, England":"Ashbourne, Derbyshire, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","Hatley, Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Pawlett","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  English: locative name from Pawlett (Somerset), which is recorded as  <i>Pavelet</i> and  <i>Paulet</i> in 1086 and  <i>Poulet</i> in 1186. The place-name may derive from Old English  <i>pāl</i> ‘stake, pole’ +  <i>flēot</i> ‘stream, estuary, inlet’.","2  English: relationship name from a double diminutive of the Middle English personal name   Paw   +  <i>-el-</i> +  <i>-ot</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Paw","meanings":["Polish: nickname from <i>paw</i> ‘peacock’.","English (London): variant of   Poe  .","Burmese (Karen): from a personal name usually forming part of a compound name, from <i>hpaw</i> ‘flower’. — Note: Since Karens do not have hereditary surnames, this name was registered as such only after immigration of its bearers to the US."]},{"name":"Powlett","meanings":["English:  see  Pawlett  ."]}]},{"name":"Florence","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval form of the Latin masculine name <i>Florentius</i> (a derivative of <i>florens</i> ‘blossoming, flourishing’) and its feminine form <i>Florentia</i>. In the Middle Ages the name was commonly borne by men (as, for example, the historian Florence of Worcester), but it is now exclusively a girl's name. This was revived in the second half of the 19th century, being given in honour of  Florence Nightingale  (  1820–1910 ), the founder of modern nursing, who organized a group of nurses to serve in the Crimean War. She herself received the name because she was born in the Italian city of Florence (Latin <i>Florentia</i>, Italian <i>Firenze</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Florance","meanings":["Medieval form of the Latin masculine name <i>Florentius</i> (a derivative of <i>florens</i> ‘blossoming, flourishing’) and its feminine form <i>Florentia</i>. In the Middle Ages the name was commonly borne by men (as, for example, the historian Florence of Worcester), but it is now exclusively a girl's name. This was revived in the second half of the 19th century, being given in honour of  Florence Nightingale  (  1820–1910 ), the founder of modern nursing, who organized a group of nurses to serve in the Crimean War. She herself received the name because she was born in the Italian city of Florence (Latin <i>Florentia</i>, Italian <i>Firenze</i>)."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Florence Pawlett was born in 1378, in England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 son with John Washborne. She died in 1450, in her hometown, at the age of 72."},"et":{"1378–1450":"1378–1450","1373–1410":"1373–1410","1390–1420":"1390–1420","1378":"1378","1410":"1410","1420":"1420","1450":"1450","1373":"1373","1390":"1390","Ashbourne, Derbyshire, England":"Ashbourne, Derbyshire, England","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Hatley, Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1378–1450":"1378–1450","1373–1410":"1373–1410","1390–1420":"1390–1420","1378":"1378","1410":"1410","1420":"1420","1450":"1450","1373":"1373","1390":"1390","Ashbourne, Derbyshire, England":"Ashbourne, Derbyshire, England","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Hatley, Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1378–1450":"1378–1450","1373–1410":"1373–1410","1390–1420":"1390–1420","1378":"1378","1410":"1410","1420":"1420","1450":"1450","1373":"1373","1390":"1390","Ashbourne, Derbyshire, England":"Ashbourne, Derbyshire, Angleterre","England":"Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Hatley, Derbyshire, England":"Der